## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why this breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`). `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The entire preemptive-abort model is removed.

### Pattern identified: **Timeout enforcement**

Your code aborts a thread after a timeout — the modern replacement is `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` with `Task.Run`.

---

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException if the
            // token fires before the task completes — this is .NET 6+ API.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async overload in new code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                             .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested
                                               && !externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // If externalToken fired, OperationCanceledException propagates as-is
    }
}
```

---

### If `work` itself must cooperate with cancellation

The above stops *waiting*, but the delegate may keep running on a thread-pool thread. For true cancellation, pass the token through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token)
                   .WaitAsync(token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work keeps running** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancelling a token doesn't inject an exception. If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion on a background thread. Insert `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always `using`/dispose it — it holds timer resources. |
| **Catching wrong exception** | Catch `OperationCanceledException`, **not** `TaskCanceledException` alone (the latter is a subclass, but other APIs throw the base type). |
| **Swallowing external cancellation** | The `when` filter on the catch distinguishes timeout from caller-requested cancellation. Without it you'd mask a parent token's signal. |
| **Blocking I/O won't cancel** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read`, etc. ignore the token. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O overloads that accept a `CancellationToken`. |
| **Uncooperative 3rd-party code** | If you truly cannot modify `work` to check the token, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout — that's the only guaranteed termination in modern .NET. |

### What was removed and why

| Old API | Status in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
